[3] Philippines, 7 suspected cases (Zamboanga, Zamboanga del Sur, Zamboanga Sibugay) - Philippines News Agency
Date: 23 Sep 2019
Source: PNA (Philippines News Agency) [edited]
https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1081211


The Department of Health (DOH) has recorded 7 suspected cases of poliomyelitis (polio) since January this year [2019] in Region 9.

Dr. Dennis Dacayanan, Regional Epidemiology and Surveillance Unit (RESU) head, disclosed Monday [23 Sep 2019] that the 7 are among the 15 cases of suspected acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) that they have recorded in the region. Dacayanan said 8 of the cases later yielded negative for polio virus.

AFP is defined as a sudden onset of paralysis or weakness in any part of the body of a child less than 15 years of age. Dacayanan said the results of 7 suspected cases are still pending with the DOH's Research Institute for Tropical Medicine (RITM).

He said 4 of the 7 suspected cases were recorded in this city, 2 in Zamboanga Sibugay and 1 in Zamboanga del Sur.

Following the discovery, the DOH official said they have strengthened surveillance after the DOH central office declared a polio outbreak on 19 Sep 2019, after confirming the re-emergence of the disease 19 years after the Philippines was declared polio-free by the World Health Organization (WHO).

Polio can be prevented through vaccination; 3 doses of oral polio vaccine and one dose of inactivated polio vaccine are needed.

Signs and symptoms of polio include headache, fever, stiff neck, vomiting, fatigue, and sudden onset of floppy arms or legs.

Proper hygiene must also be practiced by defecating in toilets, proper handwashing, making sure water is safe for drinking, and preparing and cooking food thoroughly.

[Byline: R. G. Antonet Go]

